THE ISANDLWANA Walk, which is also known as Uhambo Olungcwele, has successfully been concluded. It was launched on Thursday, 13 January, at the KZN Cultural Museum in Ulundi and was concluded on Saturday, 15 January, at the Isandlwana Mountain. The walk was initiated by actor and singer Mbuso Khoza under his organisation, Mbuso Khoza Institute of Culture and Heritage. He partnered with the Zululand District Municipality and was joined by fellow artists including Sibonile Ngubane and Portia Ncwane. The purpose of the Isandlwana Walk was to remember and honour the warriors of the Zulu kingdom. ALSO READ : DJ SUSHY’S POWERFUL MESSAGE! The event was graced by university students, artists, heritage influencers, cultural experts and traditional healers as part of commemorating the Battle of Isandlwana of 22 January 1879 – the first major encounter in the Anglo-Zulu War between the British Empire and the Zulu Kingdom. Zululand District Municipality Mayor, Reverend Thulasizwe Buthelezi, encouraged the community, especially the youth, to rally behind such activities that connect and hold their heritage and history. In his address, Buthelezi praised Khoza for this initiative. “I am extremely pleased that the youth is having interest in such a significant event that traces the footsteps of our forefathers,” he said. Inkosi Zwakele Mncwango also gave a brief lecture about the historic battle. Mbuso also revealed the Isandlawana Walk would take place on an annual basis and that a documentary for the walk was in the pipeline.    